│                                                                                        │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The crash asserts in BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands that each instruction      │
│ scheduled for removal either has no users or all of its users are already marked for   │
│ deletion. In the provided reproducer, horizontal reduction code decides to delete      │
│ several scalar instructions (including PHIs and trivial ORs), but at least one of      │
│ those instructions (e.g., %or92) still has a live user outside of the deletion set     │
│ (e.g., a final xor in the chain that remains live), which violates the invariant when  │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands tries to erase it.                                       │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The debug log shows the horizontal reduction being picked up with a calculated cost    │
│ and proceeding to vectorize. The pass then prints validations and erasures of scalars: │
│ it attempts to erase %or91, %or12.i, %or9.i, %or8.i, then PHIs %p1 and %p2, and then   │
│ %or92 and %1. Notably:                                                                 │
│ - "validating user:  %7 = xor i32 %6, %or92." appears before erasing %or92 = or i32 1, │
│ 0, meaning %or92 has a user %7 which is not going to be deleted.                       │
│ - After collecting DeadVals (RemovedInsts) and calling removeInstructionsAndOperands,  │
│ the assertion checks that users of each instruction are either empty or marked         │
│ deleted. Since %or92 has a live user (%7) that is not in the deletion set, the         │
│ assertion triggers.                                                                    │
│ - The earlier replaceUsesWithIf block only replaces uses for users present in          │
│ UserIgnoreList, which doesn't cover live users like %7 here.                           │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce/vectorizeTree constructs a set of RemovedInsts that   │
│ includes scalars with remaining external users. The pass does not ensure that all      │
│ users of these scalars are either rewritten or included in the deletion set.           │
│ Consequently, removeInstructionsAndOperands sees an instruction with live users that   │
│ are not marked deleted, violating its precondition. The invariant is correct; the      │
│ error is in our preparation of RemovedInsts prior to removal.                          │
│                                                                                        │
│ Specifically, %or92 (and potentially other scalars) are included in RemovedInsts even  │
│ though they have a use by a non-deleted instruction (%7). The selective poisoning via  │
│ UserIgnoreList does not catch this because %7 is not in UserIgnoreList.                │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We need to prevent scheduling for deletion any instruction that still has live uses    │
│ outside of the deletion set and not explicitly ignored. The safest, localized fix is   │
│ to filter RemovedInsts before calling removeInstructionsAndOperands so that we only    │
│ keep instructions whose users are all going to be deleted (or have been replaced) or   │
│ have no users.                                                                         │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit Location: in BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree, immediately before the call to               │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts)). Insert a filtering step to      │
│ build a new vector of instructions to delete (FilteredRemovedInsts) such that for each │
│ I:                                                                                     │
│ - I->use_empty() is true; or                                                           │
│ - all users U of I satisfy either isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U)) (already deleted     │
│ earlier in this function) or are contained in RemovedInsts; or                         │
│ - if UserIgnoreList is present, the user U is within UserIgnoreList (since their uses  │
│ were replaced with poison above).                                                      │
│                                                                                        │
│ This ensures the assertion in removeInstructionsAndOperands holds.                     │
│                                                                                        │
│ Proposed code change (conceptual outline to be inserted between lines ~15695 and       │
│ ~15720):                                                                               │
│ - Create a local SmallVector<Instruction *, N> FilteredRemovedInsts.                   │
│ - For each Instruction *I in RemovedInsts, check its users. If any user is not slated  │
│ for deletion (not in RemovedInsts) and is not already marked deleted and not in        │
│ UserIgnoreList, then skip I (do not push into FilteredRemovedInsts). Otherwise,        │
│ include I.                                                                             │
│ - Pass FilteredRemovedInsts to removeInstructionsAndOperands instead of RemovedInsts.  │
│                                                                                        │
│ This avoids deleting %or92 (or similar) while it still has live users, preventing the  │
│ assertion failure without relaxing correctness checks.                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ The crash stems from attempting to delete instructions that still have live users. By  │
│ filtering the to-be-deleted list prior to removal in vectorizeTree, we uphold the      │
│ invariant required by removeInstructionsAndOperands and avoid the assertion. This is a │
│ minimal and safe correction that keeps the logic of horizontal reduction intact while  │
│ ensuring the deletion preconditions are met. Expected effect: opt no longer aborts on  │
│ the reproducer; the pass either leaves such scalars in place or handles them later     │
│ once their users are rewritten, preserving IR correctness.                             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
│                                                                                        │
