has no users or all of its users are already marked for deletion. In the provided
reproducer, horizontal reduction code decides to delete several scalar instructions
(including PHIs and trivial ORs), but at least one of those instructions (e.g., %or92)
still has a live user outside of the deletion set (e.g., a final xor in the chain that
remains live), which violates the invariant when removeInstructionsAndOperands tries to
erase it.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the horizontal reduction being
picked up with a calculated cost and proceeding to vectorize. The pass then prints
validations and erasures of scalars: it attempts to erase %or91, %or12.i, %or9.i, %or8.i,
then PHIs %p1 and %p2, and then %or92 and %1. Notably:\n- \"validating user:  %7 = xor i32
%6, %or92.\" appears before erasing %or92 = or i32 1, 0, meaning %or92 has a user %7 which
is not going to be deleted.\n- After collecting DeadVals (RemovedInsts) and calling
removeInstructionsAndOperands, the assertion checks that users of each instruction are
either empty or marked deleted. Since %or92 has a live user (%7) that is not in the
deletion set, the assertion triggers.\n- The earlier replaceUsesWithIf block only replaces
uses for users present in UserIgnoreList, which doesn't cover live users like %7
here.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nHorizontalReduction::tryToReduce/vectorizeTree
constructs a set of RemovedInsts that includes scalars with remaining external users. The
pass does not ensure that all users of these scalars are either rewritten or included in
the deletion set. Consequently, removeInstructionsAndOperands sees an instruction with
live users that are not marked deleted, violating its precondition. The invariant is
correct; the error is in our preparation of RemovedInsts prior to
removal.\n\nSpecifically, %or92 (and potentially other scalars) are included in
RemovedInsts even though they have a use by a non-deleted instruction (%7). The selective
poisoning via UserIgnoreList does not catch this because %7 is not in
UserIgnoreList.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe need to prevent scheduling for deletion
any instruction that still has live uses outside of the deletion set and not explicitly
ignored. The safest, localized fix is to filter RemovedInsts before calling
removeInstructionsAndOperands so that we only keep instructions whose users are all going
to be deleted (or have been replaced) or have no users.\n\nEdit Location: in
BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree, immediately before the call to
removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts)). Insert a filtering step to build a
new vector of instructions to delete (FilteredRemovedInsts) such that for each I:\n-
I->use_empty() is true; or\n- all users U of I satisfy either
isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U)) (already deleted earlier in this function) or are
contained in RemovedInsts; or\n- if UserIgnoreList is present, the user U is within
UserIgnoreList (since their uses were replaced with poison above).\n\nThis ensures the
assertion in removeInstructionsAndOperands holds.\n\nProposed code change (conceptual
outline to be inserted between lines ~15695 and ~15720):\n- Create a local
SmallVector<Instruction *, N> FilteredRemovedInsts.\n- For each Instruction *I in
RemovedInsts, check its users. If any user is not slated for deletion (not in
RemovedInsts) and is not already marked deleted and not in UserIgnoreList, then skip I (do
not push into FilteredRemovedInsts). Otherwise, include I.\n- Pass FilteredRemovedInsts to
removeInstructionsAndOperands instead of RemovedInsts.\n\nThis avoids deleting %or92 (or
similar) while it still has live users, preventing the assertion failure without relaxing
correctness checks.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from attempting to delete
instructions that still have live users. By filtering the to-be-deleted list prior to
removal in vectorizeTree, we uphold the invariant required by
removeInstructionsAndOperands and avoid the assertion. This is a minimal and safe
correction that keeps the logic of horizontal reduction intact while ensuring the deletion
preconditions are met. Expected effect: opt no longer aborts on the reproducer; the pass
either leaves such scalars in place or handles them later once their users are rewritten,
preserving IR correctness.",
